<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Imposition" class="currentChild" href="Imposition">Imposition</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
The positioning of pages on a press sheet in such a manner that when the sheet is folded into a <a title="Signature" href="Signature">signature</a> and cut, the pages will be in the correct sequence. Imposition involves not just the correct positioning of pages on the same side of the sheet, but also the <a title="Back Printing" href="Back_Printing">back printing</a>, or the pages printed on the back of the sheet. Back-printed pages can be oriented in a variety of ways; <a title="Head-to-Head Imposition" href="Head-to-Head_Imposition">head-to-head imposition</a> involves aligning the back printing so that the top of the page on the front is opposite the top of the page on the reverse; <a title="Head-to-Foot Imposition" href="Head-to-Foot_Imposition">head-to-foot imposition</a> involves aligning the back printing such that the top of the page on the front is opposite the bottom of the page on the reverse; <a title="Head-to-Side Imposition" href="Head-to-Side_Imposition">head-to-side imposition</a> involves back printing that is at a right angle to the printing on the front. <a title="Coming-And-Going Imposition" href="Coming-And-Going_Imposition">Coming-and-going imposition</a> is a type of page sequencing in which the <a title="Recto" href="Recto">recto</a> (or right-hand) pages are in numerical sequence from the front of the book to the back, but the <a title="Verso" href="Verso">verso</a> (or left-hand) pages are sequenced such that when the book is flipped over, they are then in sequence from the back of the book to the front. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
Based on the size of the press and the press sheets to be used for a particular print job, film <a title="Negative" href="Negative">negative</a>s or <a title="Positive" href="Positive">positive</a>s of pages are stripped into the proper imposition during the film assembly stage of <a title="Prepress" href="Prepress">prepress</a>. Newer digital prepress processes also allow the output of properly-imposed pages as film negatives directly from an <a title="Imagesetter" href="Imagesetter">imagesetter</a>. (See also <a title="Stripping" href="Stripping">Stripping</a>, <a title="PrePress: Graphic Arts Photography and Flat Assembly" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/PrePress:_Graphic_Arts_Photography_and_Flat_Assembly">PrePress: Graphic Arts Photography and Flat Assembly</a>, and <a title="Prepress: Digital Prepress" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/Prepress:_Digital_Prepress">Prepress: Digital Prepress</a>.) 
</p>
